Que 5: What is the difference between synchronized method and synchronized block?
Ans: Synchronized Method is the entire method is synchronized but synchronized block is only specific code of block inside the method is synchronized.
	It locks the whole synchronized method in thread execution but in synchronized block specific it locks only specific blocks so other threads access the rest code.
	The synchronized method is slower because it locks the whole method. but the Synchronized block has better performance because only a small part is locked.
	The synchronized method is less flexible but the synchronized block is more flexible.
	Syntax:
	Synchronized Method: synchronized void methodName().
	Synchronized block: syncronized(object){}.

***********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

	
Que 6: What is ReentrantLock? How is it different from using synchronized?
Ans: ReentrantLock is a class in Java that provides a manual locking mechanism to control access to shared resources between threads.
using ReentrantLock the same thread can acquire the lock multiple times without getting blocked.
Difference:
	THe lock is automatic in synchronization and also released automatically when blocks end. but in ReentrantLock Lock is manual, we must call lock() and unlock() for locking and unlocking.
	When an exception occurs automatically release in synchronized, but in ReentrantLock we must use try-catch to ensure the unlock(). Otherwise it can cause deadlock.
	Synchronized is basic locking only. no extra control,
	ReentrantLock is more powerful features:
	tryLock() - don't wait if lock is not available
	tryLock(time) - wait for a limited time.
	In synchronized thread waits indefinitely until lock is free. but in ReentrantLock can choose wait, not and wait with timeout.

***********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************


Que 7: Why Thread.sleep() used multithreaded applications? What happens if you don't use it?
Ans: Thread.sleep pause the execution of a thread for a specified amount of time.
	It slows down the thread so other threads can run.
	When one thread sleeps, the CPU can execute the other threads.
what happened if you don't use it:
 Then threads may execute continuously without pause.
 CPU may become overloaded because threads keep running without breaks.
 Hard to observe the output because output may appear instantly, making it difficult to see how threads work.
 
